00:13:43,970 --> 00:13:45,415
Does he know that?

265
00:13:45,471 --> 00:13:47,417
Well, he will by dessert.

266
00:13:55,915 --> 00:13:57,360
Who is it?

267
00:13:57,416 --> 00:13:58,861
John Henderson.

268
00:13:58,918 --> 00:14:00,363
Come on in.

269
00:14:01,787 --> 00:14:03,357
How do I look?

270
00:14:03,422 --> 00:14:04,696
Gorgeous.

271
00:14:04,757 --> 00:14:06,361
Thanks.

272
00:14:11,931 --> 00:14:12,875
Hi, John.

273
00:14:12,932 --> 00:14:15,378
Hi. Wow, you look great.

274
00:14:15,434 --> 00:14:17,072
OK.

275
00:14:17,136 --> 00:14:19,377
Um, this is my roommate Donna.

276
00:14:19,438 --> 00:14:20,382
Hi.

277
00:14:20,439 --> 00:14:21,509
Hi.

278
00:14:24,043 --> 00:14:25,386
So, you all ready?

279
00:14:25,444 --> 00:14:27,890
Well, I'd have to
be all ready.

280
00:14:27,947 --> 00:14:29,517
I came here to get you.

281
00:14:29,582 --> 00:14:32,222
What do you mean?

282
00:14:34,453 --> 00:14:36,228
Nothing.

283
00:14:36,289 --> 00:14:37,893
Oh. Go?

284
00:14:37,957 --> 00:14:39,231
Sure.

285
00:14:40,626 --> 00:14:41,900
See you later.

286
00:14:41,961 --> 00:14:43,406
Bye.

287
00:14:48,968 --> 00:14:50,413
How's the salad? Good?

288
00:14:50,469 --> 00:14:51,914
Good. Yours?

289
00:14:51,971 --> 00:14:53,416
Good.

290
00:14:53,472 --> 00:14:54,746
Oh.

291
00:14:56,742 --> 00:14:59,848
Have you always wanted
to be a writer?

292
00:14:59,912 --> 00:15:01,858
Yes, I think I have.

293
00:15:01,914 --> 00:15:04,861
Who are some of
your favorite authors?

294
00:15:06,419 --> 00:15:08,365
Well, I like you.

295
00:15:08,421 --> 00:15:10,367
You've read my books?

296
00:15:10,423 --> 00:15:12,869
No, I mean, as a person.

297
00:15:12,925 --> 00:15:14,370
Oh.

298
00:15:14,427 --> 00:15:16,873
Did you, uh... read my book?

299
00:15:16,929 --> 00:15:20,376
No, I couldn't.
I had a really busy week.

300
00:15:21,934 --> 00:15:24,380
Did you read the flap?

301
00:15:24,437 --> 00:15:26,383
Um...no, actually,
I didn't.

302
00:15:26,439 --> 00:15:28,885
Why, what was on the flap?

303
00:15:28,941 --> 00:15:33,390
Well, you know, they summarize
the book and tell about me.

304
00:15:35,448 --> 00:15:37,894
Did you look
at anything at all?

305
00:15:37,950 --> 00:15:40,396
Um, I saw your picture
on the back.

306
00:15:40,453 --> 00:15:42,399
I thought it was cute.

307
00:15:42,455 --> 00:15:44,401
You read the picture, then.

308
00:15:45,958 --> 00:15:47,403
So, then, besides me,

309
00:15:47,460 --> 00:15:50,407
who are some of your
other favorite authors?

310
00:15:50,463 --> 00:15:51,908
Um...

311
00:15:51,964 --> 00:15:55,343
Gee, I didn't know
I'd be taking a test.

312
00:15:55,401 --> 00:15:57,347
Oh, it's not a test.

313
00:15:57,403 --> 00:15:59,679
I'm just making conversation.

314
00:16:01,240 --> 00:16:03,345
Um, let me... let me see.

315
00:16:06,412 --> 00:16:10,360
Oh, who wrote that book
about Hollywood?

316
00:16:10,416 --> 00:16:11,861
Hollywood?

317
00:16:13,419 --> 00:16:14,864
Like a coffee-table book?

318
00:16:14,920 --> 00:16:16,024
No.

319
00:16:17,423 --> 00:16:18,868
What book?

320
00:16:18,924 --> 00:16:20,369
You know, the...

321
00:16:20,426 --> 00:16:22,531
The one where they
took all those pills.

322
00:16:24,096 --> 00:16:25,370
Julia Philips.

323
00:16:25,431 --> 00:16:27,877
No, no.
I know it's not that one.

324
00:16:27,933 --> 00:16:29,378
No.

325
00:16:29,435 --> 00:16:30,880
Um...let's see...

326
00:16:32,438 --> 00:16:33,883
Jacqueline.

327
00:16:33,939 --> 00:16:35,384
Um... Jacqueline...

328
00:16:35,441 --> 00:16:36,886
Jacqueline Susann?

329
00:16:36,942 --> 00:16:38,387
Yes. I love her.

330
00:16:38,444 --> 00:16:39,889
You don't mean...

331
00:16:39,945 --> 00:16:41,390
Yes.
Valley of the Dolls.

332
00:16:41,447 --> 00:16:42,892
That's it. That was it.

333
00:16:42,948 --> 00:16:44,393
That's what you meant.

334
00:16:44,450 --> 00:16:47,397
You know, that book was written,
like, 30 years ago.

335
00:16:47,453 --> 00:16:51,902
So? What, you can't like somebody
who wrote a book a long time ago?

336
00:16:51,957 --> 00:16:53,402
No, you're right.

337
00:16:53,459 --> 00:16:55,234
Don't people like Charlie Chaplin?

338
00:16:55,294 --> 00:16:58,298
You know, when did he write?

339
00:16:58,364 --> 00:17:02,471
Charlie Chaplin wasn't a writer.
He was a comedian.

340
00:17:02,535 --> 00:17:05,516
No, he wasn't.
He was a writer.

341
00:17:05,571 --> 00:17:08,609
Tale of Two Cities,
um...

342
00:17:11,410 --> 00:17:13,356
Hey, I have an idea.

343
00:17:13,412 --> 00:17:15,085
Let's get the check.

344
00:17:17,750 --> 00:17:26,033
Help me!

345
00:17:31,430 --> 00:17:35,276
Mmm, I'm thinking about branching out
and handling entertainers.

346
00:17:36,769 --> 00:17:39,545
I wonder if that's
such a good idea.

347
00:17:39,605 --> 00:17:41,551
Can't a sports agent
handle entertainers?

348
00:17:41,607 --> 00:17:43,883
I mean, Mike Ovitz
used to handle athletes,

349
00:17:43,943 --> 00:17:45,388
so why not?

350
00:17:45,444 --> 00:17:47,754
Well, I guess you're right.

351
00:17:47,813 --> 00:17:49,759
Have you finished
your new book?

352
00:17:49,815 --> 00:17:52,386
Actually, I haven't
even started it.

353
00:17:52,451 --> 00:17:55,193
I've, uh... got a block.

354
00:17:55,254 --> 00:17:56,494
What's a block?

355
00:17:56,555 --> 00:17:58,592
Uh, it's when he can't write.

356
00:17:58,657 --> 00:18:00,830
Oh, don't tell her that.

357
00:18:00,893 --> 00:18:02,065
I can write, honey.

358
00:18:02,127 --> 00:18:04,471
I just don't know what I'm
going to write about.

359
00:18:04,530 --> 00:18:05,474
Uncle John?

360
00:18:05,531 --> 00:18:06,475
Yeah?

361
00:18:06,532 --> 00:18:08,443
Why don't you write
about a monster?

362
00:18:08,501 --> 00:18:10,174
Hey, he already did that, buddy.

363
00:18:10,236 --> 00:18:12,182
I can't do it again?

364
00:18:12,238 --> 00:18:15,185
Doesn't Stephen King
write about the same thing

365
00:18:15,241 --> 00:18:16,845
over and over and over?

366
00:18:16,909 --> 00:18:18,354
But that's Stephen King.

367
00:18:18,410 --> 00:18:19,855
What does that mean?

368
00:18:19,912 --> 00:18:22,688
She just means, you know...

369
00:18:22,748 --> 00:18:25,820
I mean, he's a big seller.

370
00:18:25,885 --> 00:18:28,195
I see. So that gives him
the right to repeat.

371
00:18:28,254 --> 00:18:29,665
I don't have that right.

372
00:18:29,722 --> 00:18:32,032
Misery was cool.

373
00:18:32,091 --> 00:18:33,536
Let's forget it.

374
00:18:33,592 --> 00:18:36,539
Besides, you shouldn't
compare yourself to anyone,

375
00:18:36,595 --> 00:18:38,074
let alone Stephen King.

376
00:18:38,130 --> 00:18:39,541
Thanks.

377
00:18:41,600 --> 00:18:43,204
Want to see my latest?

378
00:18:43,269 --> 00:18:44,373
Hmm.

379
00:18:45,771 --> 00:18:46,875
Wow.

380
00:18:46,939 --> 00:18:48,043
Yeah, huh?

381
00:18:48,107 --> 00:18:49,552
What is this?

382
00:18:49,608 --> 00:18:51,884
This is an autographed picture
of Babe Ruth.

383
00:18:51,944 --> 00:18:53,389
It is, isn't it?

384
00:18:53,445 --> 00:18:54,549
Yeah.

385
00:18:54,613 --> 00:18:56,092
Jesus. Autographed to you?

386
00:18:56,148 --> 00:18:58,150
Of course not.
I wasn't even born then.

387
00:18:58,217 --> 00:19:00,458
No, I know when you were born.
just joking.

388
00:19:00,519 --> 00:19:03,329
"To Harry, good luck.
The Babe."

389
00:19:03,389 --> 00:19:05,335
Well, you know what
you have to do.

390
00:19:05,391 --> 00:19:07,337
You have to have another kid
and name him Harry.

391
00:19:07,393 --> 00:19:08,997
Then this really becomes valuable.

392
00:19:09,061 --> 00:19:10,506
Look at this.

393
00:19:11,830 --> 00:19:12,831
Hmm.

394
00:19:12,898 --> 00:19:14,844
Know how much that's worth?

395
00:19:14,900 --> 00:19:16,345
It's the original?

396
00:19:16,402 --> 00:19:17,847
Yes, the original. Guess.

397
00:19:17,903 --> 00:19:20,349
I don't know. 2 grand?

398
00:19:20,406 --> 00:19:22,352
$50,000.

399
00:19:22,408 --> 00:19:24,854
Who is going to give you
$50,000 for this?

400
00:19:24,910 --> 00:19:26,355
The market is 11-year-olds.

401
00:19:26,412 --> 00:19:28,016
You'd be lucky to get 10 bucks

402
00:19:28,080 --> 00:19:29,525
for anything, wouldn't you?

403
00:19:29,582 --> 00:19:31,858
No. You've no idea
about this stuff.

404
00:19:31,917 --> 00:19:33,362
I guess I don't.

405
00:19:33,419 --> 00:19:35,160
Have a seat.

406
00:19:39,425 --> 00:19:40,870
So, what's wrong?

407
00:19:40,926 --> 00:19:43,372
Why does something
have to be wrong?

408
00:19:43,429 --> 00:19:49,311
Well, hey, you're here.
Something's wrong.

409
00:19:49,368 --> 00:19:51,871
You don't come here
if something isn't wrong.

410
00:19:51,937 --> 00:19:53,610
All right.
Something's wrong.

411
00:19:53,672 --> 00:19:54,878
What's the problem?

412
00:19:54,940 --> 00:19:56,851
How often do you talk to Mother?

413
00:19:56,909 --> 00:19:57,853
Every day.

414
00:19:57,910 --> 00:19:59,856
Really? Every day?

415
00:19:59,912 --> 00:20:02,085
Yeah.
Hey, look what I sent her.

416
00:20:02,147 --> 00:20:03,649
What is that?

417
00:20:03,716 --> 00:20:05,491
That's a picture phone.

418
00:20:05,551 --> 00:20:07,827
She's not going to
be able to work that.

419
00:20:07,886 --> 00:20:09,263
Why not?

420
00:20:09,321 --> 00:20:11,392
No person over 60
can operate anything like this.

421
00:20:11,457 --> 00:20:13,903
Have you ever seen what she does
with call waiting?

422
00:20:13,959 --> 00:20:15,905
This is simple.
You look in the camera.

423
00:20:15,961 --> 00:20:17,406
She'll never take the lens cap off.

424
00:20:17,463 --> 00:20:18,908
You want one?

425
00:20:18,964 --> 00:20:20,409
See, I thought maybe
the whole family

426
00:20:20,466 --> 00:20:22,412
could look at each other
when we talk.

427
00:20:22,468 --> 00:20:24,914
Well, I'm moving
out of my place,

428
00:20:24,970 --> 00:20:28,179
so I don't really
know where I'd put it.

429
00:20:28,240 --> 00:20:30,117
You're moving out
of your place?

430
00:20:30,175 --> 00:20:32,553
Yes. I'm trying
to tell you something.

431
00:20:32,611 --> 00:20:35,114
You just take the picture phone
and keep it in the box.

432
00:20:35,180 --> 00:20:37,592
Don't unwrap it.
Then wherever you go, you plug it in.

433
00:20:37,650 --> 00:20:38,924
OK, good.

434
00:20:40,486 --> 00:20:43,023
Do you feel
that Mother likes you?

435
00:20:43,088 --> 00:20:44,931
Yeah.
Of course she likes me.

436
00:20:44,990 --> 00:20:46,435
She loves me.

437
00:20:46,492 --> 00:20:50,440
But are you having the life
that she thinks you should have?

438
00:20:50,496 --> 00:20:52,442
In other words,
did she ever think

439
00:20:52,498 --> 00:20:54,102
that you shouldn't
become an agent

440
00:20:54,166 --> 00:20:55,702
because you're
not a great one?

441
00:20:55,768 --> 00:20:57,372
I'm not a great one?

442
00:20:57,436 --> 00:20:59,882
I was making $100,000
out of the gate.

443
00:20:59,938 --> 00:21:02,384
We were all blown away,
including her.

444
00:21:02,441 --> 00:21:04,387
So if I sold 5 million books,

445
00:21:04,443 --> 00:21:05,888
you think she'd like me more?

446
00:21:05,944 --> 00:21:07,389
She likes you.

447
00:21:07,446 --> 00:21:10,393
But, still, do you think
she'd be proud of me?

448
00:21:10,449 --> 00:21:13,896
Do you think she'd bond with me
the way she does with you?

449
00:21:16,955 --> 00:21:19,128
You're a complicated guy.

450
00:21:19,191 --> 00:21:21,899
Oh, so that's it, then.

451
00:21:21,960 --> 00:21:23,405
You're a simpleton?

452
00:21:23,462 --> 00:21:26,409
I'm in more of
a black-and-white business.

453
00:21:26,465 --> 00:21:28,411
everyone sees.

454
00:21:28,467 --> 00:21:30,242
Your years are not
that visible.

455
00:21:31,804 --> 00:21:34,250
But you don't seek
her approval, huh?

456
00:21:34,306 --> 00:21:36,616
I mean, obviously,
she doesn't criticize you.

457
00:21:36,675 --> 00:21:37,915
Everything is perfect.

458
00:21:37,976 --> 00:21:39,421
Of course not.

459
00:21:39,478 --> 00:21:41,424
She criticizes the way
I raise the kids.

460
00:21:41,480 --> 00:21:42,925
I mean, she has opinions.

461
00:21:42,981 --> 00:21:44,551
It doesn't get to me.

462
00:21:44,616 --> 00:21:46,926
Why does it get to me?

463
00:21:46,985 --> 00:21:48,430
I don't know.

464
00:21:48,487 --> 00:21:49,932
I mean, we're different.

465
00:21:49,988 --> 00:21:53,094
Maybe the relationship with Dad
had something to do with this.

466
00:21:53,158 --> 00:21:56,139
Maybe Dad was different with me
than he was with you.

467
00:21:57,763 --> 00:21:59,436
Maybe he was.

468
00:21:59,498 --> 00:22:01,205
Well, let me tell you something.

469
00:22:01,266 --> 00:22:03,041
This is affecting my whole life.

470
00:22:03,102 --> 00:22:07,380
I feel estranged from my own mother,
and I don't like it.

471
00:22:07,439 --> 00:22:10,249
It affects everything I do,
especially with women.

472
00:22:10,309 --> 00:22:12,380
But you ought to
just forget about it.

473
00:22:12,444 --> 00:22:13,889
You're grown up.

474
00:22:13,946 --> 00:22:15,584
I mean,
there's nothing you can do.

475
00:22:15,647 --> 00:22:17,388
Ah. I don't think
that's true.

476
00:22:17,449 --> 00:22:19,429
I've been thinking
about this a lot.

477
00:22:23,455 --> 00:22:25,901
I'm going to move
back in with Mother.

478
00:22:28,460 --> 00:22:29,996
No, you're not.

479
00:22:30,062 --> 00:22:31,973
Yeah, I am.

480
00:22:32,030 --> 00:22:34,408
That's the worst thing
I've ever heard.

481
00:22:34,466 --> 00:22:35,740
That's stupid.

482
00:22:37,302 --> 00:22:39,407
You're grown up.
What are you going to do?

483
00:22:39,471 --> 00:22:41,246
Why are you going to do that?

484
00:22:41,306 --> 00:22:43,149
You know what?
You sound a little jealous.

485
00:22:43,208 --> 00:22:44,448
Yeah, right.

486
00:22:44,510 --> 00:22:47,582
I'm jealous. That's what I want
is my old room back.

487
00:22:47,646 --> 00:22:48,920
Come on.

488
00:22:48,981 --> 00:22:51,359
Oh, man. Go see a doctor.

489
00:22:51,416 --> 00:22:53,919
No, I don't need
to see a doctor.

490
00:22:53,986 --> 00:22:55,863
I wasn't raised by a doctor.

491
00:22:55,921 --> 00:22:57,867
I was raised by my mother.

492
00:22:57,923 --> 00:23:00,199
That's who I need to see.

493
00:24:16,568 --> 00:24:17,672
Where you heading?

494
00:24:17,736 --> 00:24:19,716
Heading up north.

495
00:24:19,771 --> 00:24:20,806
Big Sur?

496
00:24:20,873 --> 00:24:22,819
No. Big Mama.

497
00:24:22,875 --> 00:24:25,082
Ha ha ha!

498
00:24:27,579 --> 00:24:30,059
What the hell does that mean?

499
00:25:21,867 --> 00:25:23,540
Hi!

500
00:25:23,602 --> 00:25:26,378
Honey,
I'm on the picture phone.

501
00:25:26,438 --> 00:25:27,917
Just a minute.

502
00:25:30,943 --> 00:25:33,549
Drove 400 miles,
she won't come out.

503
00:25:36,648 --> 00:25:39,629
More to the left, Mom.
I can't see you.

504
00:25:39,685 --> 00:25:40,993
I can see you.

505
00:25:41,053 --> 00:25:44,660
That doesn't mean I can see you.
You had it right before.

506
00:25:44,723 --> 00:25:47,897
Honey, why don't they put
the camera right where you are,

507
00:25:47,960 --> 00:25:51,237
and that way, I won't have
to move all over the place.

508
00:25:51,296 --> 00:25:53,173
Just move to the left!

509
00:25:53,231 --> 00:25:56,701
Honey, John is here.
I'll call you back.

510
00:25:56,768 --> 00:25:58,839
We didn't even get
a chance to talk.

511
00:25:58,904 --> 00:26:00,383
Move up so I can see you.

512
00:26:00,439 --> 00:26:03,010
Let me call you back.
John's here now.

513
00:26:03,075 --> 00:26:04,918
Call me back soon.

514
00:26:04,977 --> 00:26:07,924
Oh, do you want to
say hi to John?

515
00:26:07,980 --> 00:26:10,426
Do you want to try to see him?

516
00:26:10,482 --> 00:26:12,018
That's all right, Mother.

517
00:26:12,084 --> 00:26:14,360
I'll talk to you later. Bye.

518
00:26:14,419 --> 00:26:15,955
Ooh. All right, dear.

519
00:26:16,021 --> 00:26:18,365
You'll explain how to work it
next time.

520
00:26:21,093 --> 00:26:23,869
Oh, honey,
how do I tum this thing off?

521
00:26:23,929 --> 00:26:27,877
I told him I like this,
but it's driving me crazy.

522
00:26:27,933 --> 00:26:29,412
Oh, honey, you look tired.

523
00:26:31,470 --> 00:26:33,381
I just drove 400 miles.

524
00:26:33,438 --> 00:26:35,384
Can't you start with a hello

525
00:26:35,440 --> 00:26:37,420
and then move into a criticism?

526
00:26:37,476 --> 00:26:41,219
Oh, you know
I'm happy to see you.

527
00:26:41,279 --> 00:26:44,453
Now, why didn't you
want to stay in a hotel?

528
00:26:44,516 --> 00:26:46,462
I told you what's going on.

529
00:26:46,518 --> 00:26:48,725
You know, dear,
I really don't understand

530
00:26:48,787 --> 00:26:50,733
what you mean by
"the experiment"

531
00:26:50,789 --> 00:26:53,668
but listen--the couch
will do for a few nights.

532
00:26:53,725 --> 00:26:55,500
I don't want to stay
on the couch.

533
00:26:55,560 --> 00:26:57,506
I want to be here longer
than a few nights.

534
00:26:57,562 --> 00:26:59,838
I thought I could get
my old room back.

535
00:26:59,898 --> 00:27:02,003
No, dear.
That's a sewing room now.

536
00:27:02,067 --> 00:27:03,011
You sew?

537
00:27:03,068 --> 00:27:05,844
No, but I have things in there,

538
00:27:05,904 --> 00:27:08,942
and I don't want to
start going through them.

539
00:27:09,007 --> 00:27:11,180
But, Mother,
I want my room back.

540
00:27:11,243 --> 00:27:12,187
Why?

541
00:27:12,244 --> 00:27:14,190
Because it's part
of the experiment.

542
00:27:14,246 --> 00:27:17,352
I want to see what feelings
it would bring up to be in there.

543
00:27:17,416 --> 00:27:19,020
Listen, I'll clear
everything out.

544
00:27:19,084 --> 00:27:20,688
When I leave,
I'll put it all back.

545
00:27:20,752 --> 00:27:22,129
What's the big deal?

546
00:27:22,187 --> 00:27:24,360
You don't want to clear
anything out of that room.

547
00:27:24,423 --> 00:27:26,869
Sleep on it tonight,
and we'll talk about it tomorrow.

548
00:27:26,925 --> 00:27:28,871
All right,
but I know what I want.

549
00:27:28,927 --> 00:27:30,201
Want something to eat?

550
00:27:30,262 --> 00:27:31,366
Um...no.

551
00:27:31,430 --> 00:27:33,876
I made some salad,
and I have some meat loaf.

552
00:27:33,932 --> 00:27:35,206
I don't eat meat.

553
00:27:35,267 --> 00:27:37,372
Oh, that's right.
That's Jeff who loves it.

554
00:27:37,436 --> 00:27:38,710
I'll have some salad.

555
00:27:38,770 --> 00:27:40,215
Don't have salad
just for my sake.

556
00:27:40,272 --> 00:27:41,546
No, no. I'll have it.

557
00:27:41,606 --> 00:27:42,880
Are you sure you want salad?

558
00:27:42,941 --> 00:27:44,215
Yes, I want salad.

559
00:27:44,276 --> 00:27:45,550
Not just for my sake?

560
00:27:45,610 --> 00:27:47,556
Don't get into
this food stuff now, please.

561
00:27:47,612 --> 00:27:48,886
Just give me a little salad.

562
00:27:48,947 --> 00:27:50,221
I know what I could do.

563
00:27:50,282 --> 00:27:52,228
I could scrape the top
off the meat loaf.

564
00:27:52,284 --> 00:27:53,558
What would that do?

565
00:27:53,618 --> 00:27:55,222
It wouldn't be
as much meat then.

566
00:27:55,287 --> 00:27:56,493
But it's still meat.

567
00:27:56,555 --> 00:27:59,001
What difference does it make
how much you have?

568
00:27:59,057 --> 00:28:01,003
You really don't like meat, huh?

569
00:28:01,059 --> 00:28:03,335
No, Mother.
I don't like eating cows.

570
00:28:03,395 --> 00:28:08,344
Oh, honey, everything
comes from a cow.

571
00:28:08,400 --> 00:28:10,903
Everything

572
00:28:13,271 --> 00:28:15,842
Come on in, honey. Sit.

573
00:28:15,907 --> 00:28:18,854
Ah...there.

574
00:28:18,910 --> 00:28:21,857
You know, if you'd come
2 hours earlier,

575
00:28:21,913 --> 00:28:24,018
we could have had
dinner together.

576
00:28:24,082 --> 00:28:26,028
I made great beef stew.

577
00:28:31,923 --> 00:28:33,368
Here you are.

578
00:28:33,425 --> 00:28:34,870
There.

579
00:28:38,430 --> 00:28:39,875
Thanks.

580
00:28:39,931 --> 00:28:42,207
What else can I get for you?

581
00:28:42,267 --> 00:28:43,871
No, Mother, I'll tell you.

582
00:28:43,935 --> 00:28:45,881
I'm really not hungry at all.

583
00:28:45,937 --> 00:28:48,884
I ate in a truck stop,
so this is fine.

584
00:28:48,940 --> 00:28:50,886
Well, I have some
cold spaghetti,

585
00:28:50,942 --> 00:28:53,445
but it has meat sauce in it.

586
00:28:53,512 --> 00:28:55,219
Can you eat lamb chops?

587
00:28:55,280 --> 00:28:57,817
What the hell is a lamb?
It's meat!

588
00:28:57,883 --> 00:28:59,726
I told you, I don't eat it.

589
00:28:59,784 --> 00:29:01,320
Well, it's not a cow.

590
00:29:01,386 --> 00:29:04,526
I didn't know if it was the animal
you were siding with

591
00:29:04,589 --> 00:29:05,829
or the whole thing.

592
00:29:05,891 --> 00:29:07,097
The whole thing.

593
00:29:07,159 --> 00:29:08,263
Want some cheese?

594
00:29:08,326 --> 00:29:10,966
No. The salad is fine,
I promise.

595
00:29:11,029 --> 00:29:15,341
I'm going to give you
some cheese.

596
00:29:18,370 --> 00:29:20,748
That's a lot of cheese.

597
00:29:20,805 --> 00:29:22,341
Got it in hunks.

598
00:29:22,407 --> 00:29:24,353
Mother...

599
00:29:24,409 --> 00:29:26,082
Look at the date!

600
00:29:26,144 --> 00:29:27,680
It's 3 years old!

601
00:29:27,746 --> 00:29:29,692
Well, it's been in the freezer.

602
00:29:29,748 --> 00:29:32,854
Yeah, but how cheap was it that you
wanted to buy this much of it?

603
00:29:32,918 --> 00:29:34,522
Honey, this is wonderful cheese.

604
00:29:34,586 --> 00:29:37,032
It comes from Switzerland.
Very hard to get.

605
00:29:37,088 --> 00:29:39,364
How could it be hard to get?
It's all here!

606
00:29:40,425 --> 00:29:41,699
I don't want the cheese.

607
00:29:41,760 --> 00:29:42,761
Now, dear--

608
00:29:42,827 --> 00:29:45,273
Mother, stop!
I don't want any!

609
00:29:45,330 --> 00:29:46,536
Wait a minute.

610
00:29:46,598 --> 00:29:47,872
It's like This Old House

611
00:29:47,933 --> 00:29:49,879
Well, you haven't
even tried it.

612
00:29:49,935 --> 00:29:53,212
I can tell by the gross weight
I'm not going to like it.

613
00:29:53,271 --> 00:29:55,217
I like my cheeses
in the ounces.

614
00:29:55,273 --> 00:29:58,220
When they weigh as much as a Fiat,
I get worried.

615
00:29:58,276 --> 00:29:59,277
Whatever.

616
00:29:59,344 --> 00:30:00,721
Can you eat Saltines?

617
00:30:00,779 --> 00:30:02,884
Yes, of course
I can eat Saltines.

618
00:30:02,948 --> 00:30:05,554
Can't anybody?
That's what they give sick people.

619
00:30:05,617 --> 00:30:08,894
I just didn't know if there
was some sort of meat in it.

620
00:30:08,954 --> 00:30:10,729
I didn't know what they use.

621
00:30:10,789 --> 00:30:12,894
Put it away, Mother.
I don't want it.

622
00:30:12,958 --> 00:30:15,234
Just clear a portion
out of the refrigerator,

623
00:30:15,293 --> 00:30:18,240
and tomorrow, I'll go shopping
and get stuff that I like.

624
00:30:18,296 --> 00:30:19,741
You don't have to do that.

625
00:30:19,798 --> 00:30:21,004
No, I want to.

626
00:30:21,066 --> 00:30:23,376
I'm going to be here.
I want to have food to eat.

627
00:30:23,435 --> 00:30:25,574
You think you'll
be here long enough

628
00:30:25,637 --> 00:30:27,446
that you need to go shopping?

629
00:30:27,505 --> 00:30:30,918
Yes. I wish you'd understand
what I'm doing here and support it.

630
00:30:33,979 --> 00:30:35,925
Whoo!

631
00:30:35,981 --> 00:30:37,858
Yuck!

632
00:30:37,916 --> 00:30:40,556
What's wrong?
There can't be meat in that.

633
00:30:40,619 --> 00:30:42,599
This lettuce is 100 years old!

634
00:30:42,654 --> 00:30:45,658
What, did you get this from
the Smithsonian commissary?

635
00:30:45,724 --> 00:30:47,431
Honey, lettuce doesn't get old.

636
00:30:47,492 --> 00:30:50,132
Lettuce doesn't get old?
Where do you read that?

637
00:30:50,195 --> 00:30:52,038
You never heard
of wilted lettuce?

638
00:30:52,097 --> 00:30:54,304
Honey, I just took it
out of the freezer.

639
00:30:54,366 --> 00:30:55,743
You're freezing everything.

640
00:30:55,800 --> 00:30:58,644
It was a good invention,
but it wasn't meant for everything.

641
00:30:58,703 --> 00:31:00,705
That's why it's smaller
than the refrigerator.

642
00:31:00,772 --> 00:31:04,151
You're not supposed to put
everything in that little box.

643
00:31:04,209 --> 00:31:06,052
I make my salads on Monday,

644
00:31:06,111 --> 00:31:08,057
and I keep them frozen all week.

645
00:31:08,113 --> 00:31:10,184
I think I know what I'm doing.

646
00:31:10,248 --> 00:31:12,558
I know, but it doesn't
taste good to me.

647
00:31:12,617 --> 00:31:14,221
You're just not used to it.

648
00:31:14,286 --> 00:31:16,061
I don't want to get used to it.

649
00:31:16,121 --> 00:31:17,896
I want to go to the market.

650
00:31:17,956 --> 00:31:19,162
How about some sherbet?

651
00:31:19,224 --> 00:31:22,330
Uh-oh. What kind of sherbet?

652
00:31:22,394 --> 00:31:25,068
Oh, what do you mean?

653
00:31:25,130 --> 00:31:27,906
It's delicious! Mmm.

654
00:31:30,435 --> 00:31:32,437
"Sweet Tooth"?

655
00:31:32,504 --> 00:31:35,246
Where do you find Sweet Tooth?

656
00:31:35,307 --> 00:31:37,253
I never hear of these brands.

657
00:31:37,309 --> 00:31:40,222
There's a Baskin-Robbins
half a block from here.

658
00:31:40,278 --> 00:31:41,757
I wouldn't go down there.

659
00:31:41,813 --> 00:31:43,258
That's a waste of money.

660
00:31:43,315 --> 00:31:45,090
I'm not going to fall for that.

661
00:31:45,150 --> 00:31:47,596
What are you falling for?
They have ice cream in there.

662
00:31:47,652 --> 00:31:48,756
There’s no difference.

663
00:31:48,820 --> 00:31:50,595
Why should I pay
triple the amount

664
00:31:50,655 --> 00:31:54,034
when they probably go to the supermarket
and buy the very same kind?

665
00:31:54,092 --> 00:31:56,470
Mother,
the ice cream is colorless.

666
00:31:56,528 --> 00:31:59,600
Look under the protective ice.

667
00:31:59,664 --> 00:32:01,871
The protective ice?

668
00:32:01,933 --> 00:32:06,143
You've actually named the clear,
hard crap that sits on the top?

669
00:32:06,204 --> 00:32:08,878
Well, if you don't want it,
don't eat it.

670
00:32:08,940 --> 00:32:11,887
You know, when I'm down and you
give me these words of wisdom

671
00:32:11,943 --> 00:32:14,890
and you say to me, "Honey,
you don't need to see a shrink.

672
00:32:14,946 --> 00:32:16,755
Just don't be hard on yourself."

673
00:32:16,815 --> 00:32:19,887
How can I possibly do that
when I come from you?

674
00:32:19,951 --> 00:32:21,828
You're running a food museum here!

675
00:32:21,886 --> 00:32:23,888
Why can't you just
go buy fresh ice cream?

676
00:32:23,955 --> 00:32:25,559
Honey, you haven't
even tried it.

677
00:32:25,623 --> 00:32:27,398
You're making fun
of the ice cream,

678
00:32:27,459 --> 00:32:29,234
and you haven't even tasted it.

679
00:32:29,294 --> 00:32:30,398
It's wonderful sherbet.

680
00:32:30,462 --> 00:32:32,908
I don't want it.
I'm not going to taste it.

681
00:32:32,964 --> 00:32:33,942
No?

682
00:32:33,998 --> 00:32:35,409
I don't want it.

683
00:32:35,467 --> 00:32:37,003
You tell me...

684
00:32:37,068 --> 00:32:38,911
Aargh...

685
00:32:40,972 --> 00:32:42,417
Bleah!

686
00:32:42,474 --> 00:32:44,977
Oh, God, this is horribly old!

687
00:32:45,043 --> 00:32:48,923
This tastes like an orange foot!

688
00:32:48,980 --> 00:32:51,324
Oh, my God almighty!

689
00:32:51,383 --> 00:32:53,420
Phooey! Yuck!

690
00:32:53,485 --> 00:32:56,022
You're the first one
that didn't like it.

691
00:32:56,087 --> 00:32:57,532
Oh, I bet.

692
00:32:57,589 --> 00:32:59,296
Buy your own, then.

693
00:32:59,357 --> 00:33:00,700
I'm exhausted.

694
00:33:00,759 --> 00:33:02,705
I'm going to go take a bath.

695
00:33:02,761 --> 00:33:04,707
Eat whatever you want to eat.

696
00:33:04,763 --> 00:33:06,868
Just put the dishes
in the sink,

697
00:33:06,931 --> 00:33:09,377
and I'll see you in the morning,

698
00:33:09,434 --> 00:33:11,880
and then we'll talk
about the couch.

699
00:33:11,936 --> 00:33:15,713
Such a surprise to have you here.

700
00:33:15,774 --> 00:33:17,879
Sleep well, Mother.

701
00:33:51,476 --> 00:33:52,921
Honey?

702
00:33:52,977 --> 00:33:54,752
Oh. Scared me.

703
00:33:54,813 --> 00:33:56,417
What are you doing?

704
00:33:56,481 --> 00:34:00,361
I just want to see how maybe I could
clear out some of these things.

705
00:34:00,418 --> 00:34:02,694
Dear, we were going to talk
about that tomorrow.

706
00:34:02,754 --> 00:34:04,529
I don't think it's a good idea.

707
00:34:04,589 --> 00:34:07,035
Mother, I really do want to
stay in this room.

708
00:34:07,091 --> 00:34:08,570
It's important to me.

709
00:34:08,626 --> 00:34:10,663
What are you trying to do?
Remind me.

710
00:34:10,728 --> 00:34:12,708
I'm trying to
recapture a feeling.

711
00:34:12,764 --> 00:34:15,210
You want to stay in here
to recapture something.

712
00:34:15,266 --> 00:34:17,712
Yeah. I want to see what feelings
it would bring up.

713
00:34:17,769 --> 00:34:20,215
What am I going to do with all this?
just leave it.

714
00:34:20,271 --> 00:34:21,875
We'll put it
in the garage temporarily.

715
00:34:21,940 --> 00:34:22,884
We can't do that.

716
00:34:22,941 --> 00:34:23,885
Why?

717
00:34:23,942 --> 00:34:25,216
The garage is full of stuff.

718
00:34:25,276 --> 00:34:26,880
It's full of
all my high-school stuff.

719
00:34:26,945 --> 00:34:28,219
You saved everything.

720
00:34:28,279 --> 00:34:30,725
Let me move it in here,
and I'll move this back there.

721
00:34:30,782 --> 00:34:32,056
What difference does it make?

722
00:34:32,116 --> 00:34:34,062
What about the car?
You might damage it.

723
00:34:34,118 --> 00:34:35,392
I'll pull the car out.

724
00:34:35,453 --> 00:34:36,898
And you'll put it back?

725
00:34:36,955 --> 00:34:38,730
No, I will never
put it back.

726
00:34:38,790 --> 00:34:40,736
It will become
an Oldsmobile exhibit.

727
00:34:40,792 --> 00:34:43,238
We'll buy a big turntable,
it will revolve slowly,

728
00:34:43,294 --> 00:34:45,740
we'll get a good-looking girl
with a mike.

729
00:34:45,797 --> 00:34:48,573
I don't want to get
everything dusty.

730
00:34:48,633 --> 00:34:49,907
Look at this room!

731
00:34:49,968 --> 00:34:52,414
You've got chairs
piled up to the ceiling.

732
00:34:52,470 --> 00:34:54,916
What difference does it make
if they get dusty?

733
00:34:54,973 --> 00:34:56,350
I plan to use those chairs.

734
00:34:56,407 --> 00:34:58,353
In what--some sort
of a vaudeville act?

735
00:34:58,409 --> 00:35:01,356
The furniture's very heavy,
and you're not strong enough,

736
00:35:01,412 --> 00:35:02,857
and I can't help you.

737
00:35:02,914 --> 00:35:04,689
I'll get somebody
off the street.

738
00:35:04,749 --> 00:35:07,355
I can go down to Sears
and get one of those kids.

739
00:35:07,418 --> 00:35:08,863
You know how to do that?

740
00:35:08,920 --> 00:35:10,194
How to do what?

741
00:35:10,255 --> 00:35:12,201
How to choose those men
on the corner.

742
00:35:12,257 --> 00:35:13,702
It's not an art form.

743
00:35:13,758 --> 00:35:16,204
You just point to them,
and they get in the car.

744
00:35:16,261 --> 00:35:17,865
Don't overpay them.
It's insulting.

745
00:35:17,929 --> 00:35:19,704
I read where they
don't like that.

746
00:35:19,764 --> 00:35:21,368
I know.
I read the same thing.

747
00:35:21,432 --> 00:35:23,878
When they get their paycheck
and it's huge, they feel violated.

748
00:35:23,935 --> 00:35:25,710
Well, they're different than us.

749
00:35:25,770 --> 00:35:29,217
No.
You're different than them.

750
00:35:29,274 --> 00:35:30,651
Good night.

751
00:35:30,708 --> 00:35:32,710
Good night, dear.

752
00:37:32,597 --> 00:37:36,374
And...ta-da!

753
00:37:36,434 --> 00:37:38,880
Oh, this is something!

754
00:37:38,936 --> 00:37:43,214
It looks exactly like it looked
when you were in school.

755
00:37:44,942 --> 00:37:47,218
I hope you know
what you're doing.

756
00:37:48,880 --> 00:37:51,986
Honey, I'm not sure
where the camera is.

757
00:37:52,050 --> 00:37:54,428
It's the tiny hole
right above the screen.

758
00:37:54,485 --> 00:37:57,591
I don't think I have
the same one you do.

759
00:37:57,655 --> 00:38:00,329
Yes, of course you do.
It's the same phone.

760
00:38:00,391 --> 00:38:01,995
Just move to your right.

761
00:38:02,060 --> 00:38:04,233
Hold...

762
00:38:04,295 --> 00:38:05,501
To your left!

763
00:38:05,563 --> 00:38:07,338
Honey, I can't hear you!

764
00:38:07,398 --> 00:38:10,345
Mother! Ma!

765
00:38:10,401 --> 00:38:12,847
Stay there!
That's good! Hold it!

766
00:38:12,904 --> 00:38:15,680
Just stay right there.
That's fine. Don't move.

767
00:38:15,740 --> 00:38:16,946
Good enough.

768
00:38:17,008 --> 00:38:19,852
Look, I think that
he just wants to see

769
00:38:19,911 --> 00:38:22,187
what he can do
about your relationship.

770
00:38:22,246 --> 00:38:24,419
Well, what's wrong
with our relationship?

771
00:38:24,482 --> 00:38:27,691
Maybe we don't see as much
of each other as you and I,

772
00:38:27,752 --> 00:38:28,924
but it's fine.

773
00:38:28,986 --> 00:38:30,863
Just go with it
for a little while.

774
00:38:30,922 --> 00:38:32,492
I'm sure he'll get sick of it.

775
00:38:32,557 --> 00:38:35,197
Isn't there something wrong
with a grown man

776
00:38:35,259 --> 00:38:38,103
who puts his high-school things
back on the shelf?

777
00:38:38,162 --> 00:38:41,143
Well, he's a writer.
Chalk it up to that.

778
00:38:41,199 --> 00:38:44,373
Oh, I don't think that has
anything to do with writing.

779
00:38:44,435 --> 00:38:47,439
He's not that famous a writer
that he can afford to go nuts.

780
00:38:47,505 --> 00:38:50,315
He might be famous one day, Mom.
You never know.

781
00:38:50,374 --> 00:38:54,379
Really? Do you really
think that's possible?

782
00:38:54,445 --> 00:38:56,220
Do your people think so?

783
00:38:56,280 --> 00:38:57,987
My people? They're athletes.

784
00:38:58,049 --> 00:39:00,825
I don't think they
even know who he is.

785
00:39:00,885 --> 00:39:02,592
That's my point.

786
00:39:02,653 --> 00:39:05,327
Don't you worry. I'm sure
he'll get tired of it soon.

787
00:39:05,389 --> 00:39:07,164
I'll call you later.
Love you.

788
00:39:13,898 --> 00:39:15,343
Oh, my God!

789
00:39:48,766 --> 00:39:50,370
Yeah?

790
00:39:50,434 --> 00:39:51,936
Didn't see you.

791
00:39:52,003 --> 00:39:54,506
This is what you do
when you're blocked?

792
00:39:54,572 --> 00:39:55,710
Sometimes.

793
00:39:55,773 --> 00:39:57,878
I'm going to go to the market.

794
00:39:57,942 --> 00:39:59,683
Be back in about an hour.

795
00:39:59,744 --> 00:40:01,781
Oh, I want to go with you.

796
00:40:01,846 --> 00:40:03,382
Really?

797
00:40:03,447 --> 00:40:06,053
Well, come on.

798
00:40:38,482 --> 00:40:41,088
There's a space
right up here, Mother.

799
00:40:41,152 --> 00:40:42,426
Where?

800
00:40:42,486 --> 00:40:43,590
Right here!

801
00:40:43,654 --> 00:40:44,758
What space?

802
00:40:44,822 --> 00:40:45,926
There! There!

803
00:40:45,990 --> 00:40:47,936
I was looking the other way.

804
00:40:47,992 --> 00:40:50,268
I don't think it was a space.

805
00:40:50,328 --> 00:40:52,274
It has to be a space.

806
00:40:52,330 --> 00:40:54,606
Well, it's where they
put the baskets.

807
00:40:54,665 --> 00:40:56,201
Honey, I've been here before.

808
00:40:56,267 --> 00:40:57,712
You're making me nervous.

809
00:40:57,768 --> 00:41:00,374
I don't want to lose it,
that's all.

810
00:41:00,438 --> 00:41:01,712
Well, it's not--

811
00:41:01,772 --> 00:41:04,719
You're going around again.
No, no. Here. Right here.

812
00:41:04,775 --> 00:41:07,051
What are you doing?
It's right there!

813
00:41:07,111 --> 00:41:08,886
Oh, goodness.

814
00:41:08,946 --> 00:41:10,892
They didn't mark it well.

815
00:41:10,948 --> 00:41:13,224
This is like a ride
at Disneyland.

816
00:41:13,284 --> 00:41:14,729
Here we go again.

817
00:41:14,785 --> 00:41:16,890
I saw one down here
on the left.

818
00:41:16,954 --> 00:41:19,400
What do you mean, the left?
Right here!

819
00:41:19,457 --> 00:41:22,131
No. We are not
doing this again. No!

820
00:41:22,193 --> 00:41:23,399
Honey, don't do that!

821
00:41:23,461 --> 00:41:25,407
If you want to drive, drive,

822
00:41:25,463 --> 00:41:27,067
but don't grab the wheel.

823
00:41:27,131 --> 00:41:28,735
I had to do something.

824
00:41:28,799 --> 00:41:31,905
Someone had to stop us
from going around.

825
00:41:31,969 --> 00:41:34,449
This was the space?

826
00:41:35,973 --> 00:41:37,577
You want a separate basket?

827
00:41:37,642 --> 00:41:38,586
Why?

828
00:41:38,643 --> 00:41:40,589
If I have some meat
products in here--

829
00:41:40,645 --> 00:41:42,591
I don't care
if meat's in the basket.

830
00:41:42,647 --> 00:41:44,422
I just don't want to ingest it.

831
00:41:44,482 --> 00:41:46,428
I didn't know
how far you take this.

832
00:41:46,484 --> 00:41:48,430
No, we can use the same basket.

833
00:41:48,486 --> 00:41:49,931
I think it's appropriate.

834
00:41:49,987 --> 00:41:51,261
Oh. OK.

835
00:41:52,857 --> 00:41:54,928
You want some peanut butter?

836
00:41:54,992 --> 00:41:57,370
As a matter of fact, I do.

837
00:41:59,430 --> 00:42:00,875
"New-Taste"?

838
00:42:00,932 --> 00:42:02,377
Mm-hmm.

839
00:42:02,433 --> 00:42:04,379
I'm going to get the organic.

840
00:42:04,435 --> 00:42:06,381
Oh, honey,
there’s no difference.

841
00:42:06,437 --> 00:42:08,383
Yeah, but I like the organic.

842
00:42:08,439 --> 00:42:10,385
But there's no reason
to pay extra.

843
00:42:10,441 --> 00:42:12,387
This all comes from
the same place.

844
00:42:12,443 --> 00:42:14,320
The man told me
it's just the label.

845
00:42:14,378 --> 00:42:16,221
I don't think that's
necessarily true,

846
00:42:16,280 --> 00:42:18,726
but in any case, I'm buying
my own peanut butter.

847
00:42:18,783 --> 00:42:20,057
I want the organic.

848
00:42:20,117 --> 00:42:22,063
I don't know why you
want to waste the money.

849
00:42:22,119 --> 00:42:24,065
Why do you want to
throw it all away?

850
00:42:24,121 --> 00:42:26,397
Because that's exactly
what I want to do.

851
00:42:26,457 --> 00:42:29,233
I want an experience where we
throw away 91 cents together.

852
00:42:29,293 --> 00:42:30,738
You throw it away.

853
00:42:30,795 --> 00:42:34,072
New-Taste is as good as any of this,
and I won't be fooled.

854
00:42:34,131 --> 00:42:35,075
Organic!

855
00:42:36,634 --> 00:42:37,908
I have an idea.

856
00:42:37,969 --> 00:42:40,916
Let's buy the most expensive
jelly in the market.

857
00:42:40,972 --> 00:42:42,417
Oh, honey, you're something.

858
00:42:42,473 --> 00:42:45,579
Come on. What do you think
the most expensive jelly is?

859
00:42:45,643 --> 00:42:47,919
I don't buy jelly.
I don't know.

860
00:42:47,979 --> 00:42:49,925
Oh, this looks very good.

861
00:42:49,981 --> 00:42:51,255
Oh, don't get that!

862
00:42:51,315 --> 00:42:52,589
Why?

863
00:42:52,650 --> 00:42:55,529
Because it's too expensive.
That's a waste of money.

864
00:42:55,586 --> 00:42:58,362
Look, you can get
a whole jar here for $2.50.

865
00:42:58,422 --> 00:43:00,368
Why would you want
to spend $10.95?

866
00:43:00,424 --> 00:43:02,370
Because, thank God,
I can afford it,

867
00:43:02,426 --> 00:43:03,871
and it might be good.

868
00:43:03,928 --> 00:43:06,204
Come on, Mother.
Let's experience this together.

869
00:43:06,263 --> 00:43:07,867
I don't want this experience!

870
00:43:07,932 --> 00:43:10,378
You're fooled by these names,
all that fancy wrapping.

871
00:43:10,434 --> 00:43:12,038
I'm not fooled by anything.

872
00:43:12,103 --> 00:43:14,049
This isn't what
the experiment's about.

873
00:43:14,105 --> 00:43:15,709
It's not about being fooled.

874
00:43:15,773 --> 00:43:17,047
It's about splurging.

875
00:43:17,108 --> 00:43:18,712
You see, I realize something.

876
00:43:18,776 --> 00:43:21,052
I think you treat yourself
very cheaply,

877
00:43:21,112 --> 00:43:22,557
and I think therefore

878
00:43:22,613 --> 00:43:24,559
you have instilled
that into me.

879
00:43:24,615 --> 00:43:26,891
I don't treat myself
cheaply at all.

880
00:43:26,951 --> 00:43:29,727
I lived through The Depression.
You didn't.

881
00:43:29,787 --> 00:43:31,733
The Depression!
You were 2.

882
00:43:31,789 --> 00:43:34,395
By the way, things
aren't so great right now.

883
00:43:34,458 --> 00:43:36,062
Well, it's not the thirties.

884
00:43:36,127 --> 00:43:39,404
You don't have to
wait in line to buy bread.

885
00:43:42,800 --> 00:43:44,507
Yes. Sourdough, please.

886
00:43:48,005 --> 00:43:50,747
You know, I've heard
this Depression story a lot,

887
00:43:50,808 --> 00:43:52,754
but I don't know
what it has to do

888
00:43:52,810 --> 00:43:54,414
with splurging for jam now.

889
00:43:54,478 --> 00:43:56,355
We're in the nineties, Mother.

890
00:43:56,414 --> 00:43:57,688
It's fancy-jam time.

891
00:43:57,748 --> 00:43:59,193
See, I realize something.

892
00:43:59,250 --> 00:44:00,854
We don't like ourselves enough.

893
00:44:00,918 --> 00:44:02,522
You don't give yourself anything.

894
00:44:02,586 --> 00:44:04,190
I don't give myself anything.

895
00:44:04,255 --> 00:44:05,529
It's all so clear!

896
00:44:05,589 --> 00:44:09,036
Shh. Honey, I don't want
to have this discussion now.

897
00:44:09,093 --> 00:44:10,868
I like myself very much.

898
00:44:10,928 --> 00:44:14,535
Just because I don't want to
spend $10 for bullshit jam

899
00:44:14,598 --> 00:44:17,875
has nothing to do with
what I feel about myself!

900
00:44:17,935 --> 00:44:20,882
I never heard you use
the word bullshit before.

901
00:44:20,938 --> 00:44:23,544
You never heard me
use a lot of words.

902
00:44:23,607 --> 00:44:24,881
Oh! What a waste.

903
00:44:24,942 --> 00:44:26,888
For God's sakes,
looks like a toy!

904
00:44:26,944 --> 00:44:29,891
The checker's going to have
a good laugh over this.

905
00:44:29,947 --> 00:44:32,223
Mother, can't you just
forget about it?

906
00:44:32,283 --> 00:44:34,388
Can't you throw
caution to the wind?

907
00:44:34,452 --> 00:44:37,899
Caution I can throw all day.
jelly is another matter.

908
00:44:37,955 --> 00:44:39,730
My goodness, a brand.

909
00:44:39,790 --> 00:44:41,394
What’s the matter?

910
00:44:41,459 --> 00:44:43,405
Don't they make New-Nuts?

911
00:44:43,461 --> 00:44:45,407
I enjoy my Grape-Nuts.

912
00:44:45,463 --> 00:44:46,908
I know you do.

913
00:44:50,935 --> 00:44:53,916
Hmm, I need some Sweet Tooth.

914
00:45:05,916 --> 00:45:08,692
<i>Shoppers,
there's no waiting at check stand 5.</i>

915
00:45:08,752 --> 00:45:10,356
<i>No waiting, check stand 5.</i>

916
00:45:10,421 --> 00:45:13,368
If you tell me there's
a difference between salt,

917
00:45:13,424 --> 00:45:15,370
I'm really going to get upset.

918
00:45:15,426 --> 00:45:17,702
You do not know how to market.

919
00:45:17,761 --> 00:45:20,367
No, I know there's
no difference between salt.

920
00:45:20,431 --> 00:45:22,377
I know salt's all the same.

921
00:45:22,433 --> 00:45:24,037
It's all all the same!

922
00:45:24,101 --> 00:45:26,103
It's not all all the same!

923
00:45:26,170 --> 00:45:28,047
Beatrice! Hello!
This is my sister.

924
00:45:28,105 --> 00:45:30,051
Sis, this is
my neighbor Beatrice.

925
00:45:30,107 --> 00:45:31,415
How do you do?

926
00:45:31,475 --> 00:45:32,715
I forget your name.

927
00:45:32,776 --> 00:45:34,449
Alice.

928
00:45:34,512 --> 00:45:36,355
So nice to see you, Beatrice.

929
00:45:36,413 --> 00:45:38,893
Alice is going to
be here for a week,

930
00:45:38,949 --> 00:45:41,225
and then she's taking
a cruise to Mexico.

931
00:45:41,285 --> 00:45:42,730
Oh, my-- a cruise!

932
00:45:42,786 --> 00:45:44,060
Oh, my!

933
00:45:44,121 --> 00:45:45,566
I'm, uh, John.

934
00:45:45,623 --> 00:45:47,933
This is my son--
the other one.

935
00:45:47,992 --> 00:45:49,062
Oh.

936
00:45:49,126 --> 00:45:51,072
He's staying with me
for a while.

937
00:45:51,128 --> 00:45:52,402
He likes this jelly.

938
00:45:52,463 --> 00:45:53,771
Look at that!

939
00:45:53,831 --> 00:45:55,868
Oh, I've heard of that.
It's organic.

940
00:45:55,933 --> 00:45:57,344
You've heard of it?

941
00:45:57,401 --> 00:46:00,348
Oh, yes. They're very big
in the catalog business.

942
00:46:00,404 --> 00:46:01,849
Really!

943
00:46:01,906 --> 00:46:05,353
Yes. I hear their jelly is wonderful,
and you know what else?

944
00:46:05,409 --> 00:46:09,221
They have a peanut butter for $12
that's out of this world.

945
00:46:09,280 --> 00:46:11,692
Well, just think of that.

946
00:46:11,749 --> 00:46:13,524
Leave it to my son.

947
00:46:13,584 --> 00:46:15,621
So, you're the writer?

948
00:46:15,686 --> 00:46:16,858
Yes.

949
00:46:16,921 --> 00:46:19,026
Well, he hasn't written
anything for a while,

950
00:46:19,089 --> 00:46:21,035
but he's working on a new book.

951
00:46:21,091 --> 00:46:22,661
Thanks for the intro, Mother.

952
00:46:22,726 --> 00:46:24,137
What are you writing?

953
00:46:24,195 --> 00:46:26,539
I'm working on
a science fiction novel.

954
00:46:26,597 --> 00:46:27,837
Like Stephen King.

955
00:46:27,898 --> 00:46:29,673
- Whoo!
- Whoo!

956
00:46:29,733 --> 00:46:32,714
Now, Stephen King
could afford this jelly.

957
00:46:32,770 --> 00:46:34,716
My son, I'm not so sure.

958
00:46:35,973 --> 00:46:38,214
Let's go. We got
a lot of shopping to do.

959
00:46:38,275 --> 00:46:39,253
Excuse us.

960
00:46:39,310 --> 00:46:41,051
I will speak to you, Beatrice.

961
00:46:41,111 --> 00:46:42,215
Nice to see you.

962
00:46:42,279 --> 00:46:43,883
Nice to see you, too, John.

963
00:46:43,948 --> 00:46:46,224
Nice to see you.
Have a nice trip to Mexico.

964
00:46:46,283 --> 00:46:47,227
Thank you.

965
00:46:47,284 --> 00:46:48,388
Don't drink the water.

966
00:46:48,452 --> 00:46:49,863
You see what you do?

967
00:46:49,920 --> 00:46:51,729
All you do
is apologize for me!

968
00:46:51,789 --> 00:46:53,393
I don't apologize
for you at all.

969
00:46:53,457 --> 00:46:56,165
Maybe I am a little embarrassed
about the jelly. So what?

970
00:46:56,227 --> 00:46:58,173
Why would you be embarrassed
about the jelly?

971
00:46:58,229 --> 00:46:59,503
Didn't her sister like it?

972
00:46:59,563 --> 00:47:01,008
Her sister doesn't know anything.

973
00:47:01,065 --> 00:47:02,840
You want to know
something about her?

974
00:47:02,900 --> 00:47:04,174
No, I really don't.

975
00:47:04,235 --> 00:47:06,681
She was in some sort
of institution for a few years.

976
00:47:06,737 --> 00:47:08,341
Nobody knows what really happened.

977
00:47:08,405 --> 00:47:11,011
She went insane for spending
a few dollars more for her food.

978
00:47:12,409 --> 00:47:13,513
Oh, my goodness!

979
00:47:13,577 --> 00:47:14,715
Oh, my.

980
00:47:14,778 --> 00:47:16,018
What did we do?

981
00:47:16,080 --> 00:47:18,356
We must have come around
the same way.

982
00:47:18,415 --> 00:47:19,689
I told you.

983
00:47:19,750 --> 00:47:21,195
This market's so confusing.

984
00:47:21,252 --> 00:47:22,697
I thought this was
the freezer.

985
00:47:22,753 --> 00:47:24,198
They don't have a freezer.

986
00:47:24,255 --> 00:47:25,359
Of course they do.

987
00:47:25,422 --> 00:47:27,368
Where were you trying to go?

988
00:47:27,424 --> 00:47:28,869
To the freezer.

989
00:47:28,926 --> 00:47:31,372
And you came around
the same way?

990
00:47:31,428 --> 00:47:33,032
That's so funny!

991
00:47:33,097 --> 00:47:34,838
That is so funny!

992
00:47:34,898 --> 00:47:36,377
It's not that funny.

993
00:47:36,433 --> 00:47:37,810
Mother, let's go.

994
00:47:37,868 --> 00:47:39,245
We're right back
where we started.

995
00:47:39,303 --> 00:47:40,873
You know what they just did?

996
00:47:40,938 --> 00:47:42,212
Don't tell the clerk!

997
00:47:43,774 --> 00:47:46,550
We're going to turn into skeletons
with this conversation.

998
00:47:46,610 --> 00:47:48,146
Can you believe this?

999
00:47:48,212 --> 00:47:50,886
Mother, I beg you, let's go.

1000
00:47:50,948 --> 00:47:52,723
Oh, he wants to go.

1001
00:47:52,783 --> 00:47:55,423
That's so funny!
I'll talk to you later.

1002
00:47:55,486 --> 00:47:58,330
Come on, honey.
Let's get your nonmeat things.

1003
00:47:59,890 --> 00:48:01,335
That's very funny.

1004
00:48:23,080 --> 00:48:24,354
Honey, look.

1005
00:48:24,415 --> 00:48:26,019
I cleared out the refrigerator.

1006
00:48:26,083 --> 00:48:28,359
I'm going to give you
the right-hand side,

1007
00:48:28,419 --> 00:48:30,365
and I'll put your stuff there.

1008
00:48:30,421 --> 00:48:33,027
It's like It Happened One Night
for food.

1009
00:48:33,090 --> 00:48:36,367
Oh, I love that movie.
Clark Gable was wonderful.

1010
00:48:36,427 --> 00:48:39,374
Do you really want to separate
the refrigerator?

1011
00:48:39,430 --> 00:48:41,706
Oh, yes, dear.
It'll be much easier.

1012
00:48:41,765 --> 00:48:44,371
That way you won't
accidentally eat some meat.

1013
00:48:44,435 --> 00:48:47,041
It's good that you
know that about me.

1014
00:48:47,104 --> 00:48:49,380
I accidentally eat things
all day long.

1015
00:48:57,781 --> 00:48:59,556
What are you doing?

1016
00:48:59,616 --> 00:49:02,825
I can't get it to fit
completely on my side.

1017
00:49:02,886 --> 00:49:06,424
It's just going to have
to stick over a little.

1018
00:49:06,490 --> 00:49:09,494
Mother, would you forget
the separation?

1019
00:49:09,560 --> 00:49:11,335
Just leave the refrigerator alone.

1020
00:49:11,395 --> 00:49:13,671
I can get the stuff
that I like.

1021
00:49:13,731 --> 00:49:15,836
I just thought I'd
make it easier for you.

1022
00:49:15,899 --> 00:49:17,344
Then don't manage the food.

1023
00:49:17,401 --> 00:49:19,347
My eyes are connected
to my brain

1024
00:49:19,403 --> 00:49:20,848
like in a real person.

1025
00:49:20,904 --> 00:49:23,510
I know exactly what it is
that I want to eat.

1026
00:49:23,574 --> 00:49:26,680
Fine. If you'd rather not
divide it up, we don't divide it up.

1027
00:49:26,744 --> 00:49:28,849
Would you like
some of your food now?

1028
00:49:28,912 --> 00:49:30,516
Yes. I'm a little hungry.

1029
00:49:30,581 --> 00:49:32,185
Let me make you something.

1030
00:49:32,249 --> 00:49:35,025
Why don't you set the table
and sit down?

1031
00:49:36,587 --> 00:49:39,693
Honey, tell me again,
because people will start asking--

1032
00:49:39,757 --> 00:49:41,828
You're here why?

1033
00:49:41,892 --> 00:49:43,200
Why?

1034
00:49:43,260 --> 00:49:46,605
Well, it's complicated, Mother,
but you know why.

1035
00:49:46,663 --> 00:49:49,542
Well, you're having problems,
and you're blaming me.

1036
00:49:49,600 --> 00:49:50,704
Is that it?

1037
00:49:50,768 --> 00:49:52,645
I'm not blaming anyone.

1038
00:49:52,703 --> 00:49:55,377
It's just that things
aren't working out so great

1039
00:49:55,439 --> 00:49:57,885
with the women
in my life right now,

1040
00:49:57,941 --> 00:50:01,388
and I feel that, until I
can figure this situation out,

1041
00:50:01,445 --> 00:50:04,892
I probably will never be able
to figure that situation out.

1042
00:50:04,948 --> 00:50:07,224
So, you know,
whatever I learn here,

1043
00:50:07,284 --> 00:50:10,891
I'll take into that part
of my life and apply it there.

1044
00:50:10,954 --> 00:50:13,696
Hey! That's a very
good way to say it.

1045
00:50:13,757 --> 00:50:15,566
Hmm?
Oh, I wasn't listening.

1046
00:50:15,626 --> 00:50:16,900
Tell them what?

1047
00:50:16,960 --> 00:50:18,735
This is one of the problems.

1048
00:50:18,796 --> 00:50:20,400
Just don't tell them anything.

1049
00:50:20,464 --> 00:50:21,807
Forget it.

1050
00:50:21,865 --> 00:50:25,904
Yes. I could pretend you're here
for just a regular reason.

1051
00:50:25,969 --> 00:50:28,575
Yeah--like a visit.
I'm your son.

1052
00:50:28,639 --> 00:50:31,745
Yes, of course. You could be here
for any kind of a reason.

1053
00:50:31,809 --> 00:50:34,085
For example, you could
have injured yourself,

1054
00:50:34,144 --> 00:50:36,420
and you need me
to take care of you.

1055
00:50:36,480 --> 00:50:38,756
I'm not going to limp
for you, Mother.

1056
00:50:38,816 --> 00:50:40,420
No, no.
Some internal injury.

1057
00:50:42,252 --> 00:50:45,597
So you're not making it work
with the women, dear?

1058
00:50:45,656 --> 00:50:48,603
No. Things aren't going
so great right now.

1059
00:50:48,659 --> 00:50:50,605
Oh, Karen was lovely.

1060
00:50:50,661 --> 00:50:52,607
What was the problem there again?

1061
00:50:52,663 --> 00:50:54,267
She didn't support me.

1062
00:50:54,331 --> 00:50:55,708
Did you support her?

1063
00:50:55,766 --> 00:50:57,268
Yeah, I supported her.

1064
00:50:57,334 --> 00:50:59,871
Did you, dear?
I remember when she want...

1065
00:50:59,937 --> 00:51:01,541
Oh, I forget which one.

1066
00:51:01,605 --> 00:51:04,051
What did she want to do
that you didn't want?

1067
00:51:04,107 --> 00:51:05,051
Leave me.

1068
00:51:05,108 --> 00:51:06,883
Oh. Why would you
support that?

1069
00:51:06,944 --> 00:51:09,891
The hell with her, dear.
She wasn't that cute anyway.

1070
00:51:09,947 --> 00:51:11,551
Mother, I'm fine with her.

1071
00:51:11,615 --> 00:51:13,720
We don't have to trash her looks.

1072
00:51:13,784 --> 00:51:15,092
What are you doing?

1073
00:51:15,152 --> 00:51:18,395
Stop! No more food!
It's like Fantasia!

1074
00:51:18,455 --> 00:51:20,059
You said you were hungry.

1075
00:51:20,123 --> 00:51:21,397
For my whole life,

1076
00:51:21,458 --> 00:51:24,234
I've never been able to deal
with these food questions.

1077
00:51:24,294 --> 00:51:25,739
You ask me if I'm hungry,

1078
00:51:25,796 --> 00:51:27,571
I tell you yes,
you bring me food.

1079
00:51:27,631 --> 00:51:29,076
You ask me if I'm hungry,

1080
00:51:29,132 --> 00:51:30,907
I tell you no,
you bring me food.

1081
00:51:30,968 --> 00:51:32,413
You ask me the questions,

1082
00:51:32,469 --> 00:51:33,914
but you don't listen
to the answers,

1083
00:51:33,971 --> 00:51:35,416
so I know I'm
going to get food

1084
00:51:35,472 --> 00:51:36,917
no matter what I tell you.

1085
00:51:36,974 --> 00:51:39,420
Therefore, I adjust how hungry
I tell you I am

1086
00:51:39,476 --> 00:51:41,752
to know how much food
I'm going to get.

1087
00:51:41,812 --> 00:51:44,122
From now on,
just bring what you want.

1088
00:51:44,181 --> 00:51:46,422
Really. I'll eat
what you bring me,

1089
00:51:46,483 --> 00:51:48,588
or I won't eat what
you bring me.

1090
00:51:48,652 --> 00:51:49,926
It doesn't matter.

1091
00:51:49,987 --> 00:51:52,934
Bring it anyway, and that's
the end of the food deal.

1092
00:51:52,990 --> 00:51:56,733
Honey, I never knew it was
this much of a problem.

1093
00:51:56,793 --> 00:51:59,364
I will never ask you
about food anymore.

1094
00:51:59,429 --> 00:52:01,375
Oh, Mother, you can ask me,

1095
00:52:01,431 --> 00:52:03,377
but you know what I mean.

1096
00:52:03,433 --> 00:52:06,039
Oh, I just wish
your father were alive

1097
00:52:06,103 --> 00:52:09,050
so he could take
a little of this blame.

1098
00:52:09,106 --> 00:52:11,052
Is that a joke?

1099
00:52:11,108 --> 00:52:12,883
Yes, it is, honey.

1100
00:52:12,943 --> 00:52:15,890
Every time you say something funny,
I'm shocked.

1101
00:52:15,946 --> 00:52:17,050
I know.

1102
00:52:17,114 --> 00:52:20,391
You must think of me
as some sort of moron.

1103
00:52:20,450 --> 00:52:22,054
No, no. Not a moron.

1104
00:52:22,119 --> 00:52:24,395
Just someone
who thinks I'm a moron.

1105
00:52:24,454 --> 00:52:26,559
Well, it takes one
to know one,

1106
00:52:26,623 --> 00:52:27,897
doesn't it, dear?

1107
00:52:29,459 --> 00:52:31,405
So, let me ask you something.

1108
00:52:31,461 --> 00:52:34,067
The son does get more
from his mother,

1109
00:52:34,131 --> 00:52:35,735
for the most part, anyway,

1110
00:52:35,799 --> 00:52:37,403
than his father,
doesn't he?

1111
00:52:37,467 --> 00:52:40,073
YES, in your case,
but not all the time.

1112
00:52:40,137 --> 00:52:43,141
Well, who instilled
the cheapness and self-loathing?

1113
00:52:43,206 --> 00:52:44,913
You, right?

1114
00:52:44,975 --> 00:52:46,921
Dear, I'm tired.

1115
00:52:46,977 --> 00:52:49,389
We can berate me tomorrow.

1116
00:52:50,981 --> 00:52:52,255
I love you, Mother.

1117
00:52:52,316 --> 00:52:54,125
You know,
if you talk to the women

1118
00:52:54,184 --> 00:52:56,027
the way you talk to me
sometimes,

1119
00:52:56,086 --> 00:52:58,225
I can see why
they all leave you.

1120
00:52:58,288 --> 00:53:00,199
They didn't all leave me.

1121
00:53:00,257 --> 00:53:01,861
I left some of them.

1122
00:53:01,925 --> 00:53:03,871
Really!

1123
00:53:03,927 --> 00:53:05,873
I didn't know that.

1124
00:53:17,941 --> 00:53:20,421
It is morning
on this strange planet.

1125
00:53:20,477 --> 00:53:23,083
We do not know
where we are,

1126
00:53:23,146 --> 00:53:26,218
but we are safe,
at least for the moment.

1127
00:53:26,283 --> 00:53:29,992
What is outside,
no one will ever know.

1128
00:53:31,822 --> 00:53:34,359
What is outside, nobody..

